9–1537","1425–1530":"1425–1530","1430–Female":"1430–Deceased","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1479":"1479","1467":"1467","Abt 1480":"about 1480","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1475":"1475","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","1537":"1537","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne Circuit, Derbyshire, England","Barlow, Derbyshire, England":"Barlow, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barlow","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Barlow, especially those in Lancashire and Yorkshire. The former is named with Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’; the latter probably has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":9,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Barlow was born in 1446, in Barlow, Derbyshire, England, her father, Robert Barlow, was 21 and her mother, Elena Cockayne, was 16. She married Thomas Cokayne in 1475, in Barlow, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died about 1480, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1446–Abt 1480":"1446–umbes 1480","1446–1480":"1446–1480","1441–1488":"1441–1488","1467–Male":"1467–Surnud","1470–1483":"1470–1483","1479–1537":"1479–1537","1425–1530":"1425–1530","1430–Female":"1430–Surnud","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1479":"1479","1467":"1467","Abt 1480":"umbes 1480","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1475":"1475","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","1537":"1537","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne Circuit, Derbyshire, England","Barlow, Derbyshire, England":"Barlow, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1446–Abt 1480":"1446–noin 1480","1446–1480":"1446–1480","1441–1488":"1441–1488","1467–Male":"1467–Kuollut","1470–1483":"1470–1483","1479–1537":"1479–1537","1425–1530":"1425–1530","1430–Female":"1430–Kuollut","1483":"1483","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1425":"1425","1446":"1446","1479":"1479","1467":"1467","Abt 1480":"noin 1480","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1475":"1475","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","1441":"1441","1537":"1537","Ashbourne, Derbyshire, England":"Ashbourne Circuit, Derbyshire, England","Barlow, Derbyshire, Engl